448","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","about 1384":"circa 1384","1416":"1416",", Leicester, England, Great Britain":"Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Thurlaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurlaston, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shoby, Leicestershire, England":"Shoby, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1336–":"1336–Deceased","1336–1400":"1336–1400","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1374–Female":"1374–Deceased","1376–1415":"1376–1415","1382–1448":"1382–1448","1384–1416":"1384–1416","1336–Female":"1336–Deceased","1374":"1374","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","about 1384":"about 1384","1416":"1416",", Leicester, England, Great Britain":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Thurlaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurlaston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Shoby, Leicestershire, England":"Shoby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Frisby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Frisby on the Wreake or Frisby by Gaulby, or another lost Frisby in Leicestershire, all named with Old Norse <i>Frīsa</i> ‘Frisians’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farm, settlement’, meaning ‘The farmstead of the Frisians’. Compare with   Fries  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Frisbie","meanings":["English: variant of   Frisby  ."]},{"name":"Fries","meanings":["German, Dutch, Jewish (from the Netherlands), Danish, and Swedish: ethnic name for someone from Friesland, province in the Netherlands and a region in northwestern Germany, in the Middle Ages part of the larger northwest region Fresia. This form of the surname is rare in the Netherlands but very common in Germany. Compare   De Fries   and   De Vries  .","German, Dutch, Danish, and Swedish: from the personal name <i>Friso</i>, which refers to the ethnic name (see 1 above).","South German: occupational name for a builder of dams and dikes. The word was used in this sense in various parts of Germany and Switzerland during the Middle Ages, and is perhaps a transferred use of the ethnic term, dike building being a characteristic occupation of Frieslanders."]},{"name":"Frisbee","meanings":["English: variant of   Frisby  ."]},{"name":"Frisbey","meanings":["English: variant of   Frisby  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":46,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":119,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Frisby was born in 1336, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England. She married John Brooksby, Esquire in 1366, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1336–":"1336–Surnud","1336–1400":"1336–1400","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1376–1415":"1376–1415","1382–1448":"1382–1448","1384–1416":"1384–1416","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1374":"1374","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","about 1384":"umbes 1384","1416":"1416",", Leicester, England, Great Britain":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Thurlaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurlaston, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shoby, Leicestershire, England":"Shoby, Leicestershire, Ingl